WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.000
Hon, Minister, Member, Select Committee, House of Representatives.

2
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:52.840
Good afternoon and welcome to the Social Services and the Exli Committee.

3
00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:58.439
So we have the Ministry of Sport, Pacific Peoples, this afternoon too, give us some information

4
00:00:58.439 --> 00:01:02.920
regarding that long-term insights briefing. And I think we have Jordan and Bernadette with

5
00:01:02.920 --> 00:01:07.519
us. We've got a 45-minute here. Time is yours if you want to leave some time towards the end

6
00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:10.640
for questions, please, for what we're going to do so.

7
00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:17.719
Fafte Lava and thank you for the opportunity to appear before you today. Firstly, if I

8
00:01:17.719 --> 00:01:24.280
can just introduce Bernadette Scanlon, our Deputy Secretary of Policy and Insights, who will

9
00:01:24.280 --> 00:01:31.359
be responding with me today. And if you just bear with me, I just have some opening comments,

10
00:01:31.359 --> 00:01:36.280
which will take about 10 minutes. So can I just begin by acknowledging the enduring

11
00:01:36.280 --> 00:01:41.879
kinship ties that bind Māori and Pacific peoples in this nation? These are not new

12
00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:50.280
connections formed by migration alone. They are ancient relationships shaped by navigation,

13
00:01:50.280 --> 00:01:58.680
shared cosmologies, and here in New Zealand, as early as the 1920s and 1930s, by the long-standing

14
00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:05.599
role of iwi in welcoming and hosting and looking after Pacific families as they made their homes

15
00:02:05.599 --> 00:02:12.680
on these shores and within the boundaries of various iwi around the country. There's

16
00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:18.319
no other country in the world that can claim this strong kinship link with Pacific

17
00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:25.719
nations. Through the development of this briefing, we heard many stories of iwi exercising their

18
00:02:25.719 --> 00:02:31.919
stewardship role, extending their resources, their manaki tanga, and their services to

19
00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:38.639
ensure Pacific peoples and families were cared for. These stories matter because they remind

20
00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:45.560
us that Pacific settlement in New Zealand has always been relational, grounded in whakapapa,

21
00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:52.039
place, and mutual responsibility. Over generations, these relationships have

22
00:02:52.039 --> 00:02:59.479
deepened into marriages, shared communities, shared churches, shared schools, shared

23
00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:06.159
struggles, and increasingly shared opportunities have produced a growing cohort of

24
00:03:06.159 --> 00:03:11.640
people who claim rightly and proudly kinship ties to both Māori and Pacific

25
00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:18.840
worlds. This is not a marginal phenomenon. It's a distinctive and consequential demographic shift

26
00:03:18.840 --> 00:03:25.240
underway in New Zealand. The long-term insights briefing deliberately places a ring around

27
00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:32.280
this population, not because they are separate, but because ethnic classification can render them

28
00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:39.400
statistically invisible, even as the influence becomes increasingly visible in our communities,

29
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:46.680
our classrooms, and our workplaces. If we want good long-term policy, we need to be honest

30
00:03:46.680 --> 00:03:53.800
about who's coming through the gate. And what the data is telling us is striking. The average age

31
00:03:53.800 --> 00:04:02.040
of people who identify with both Māori and Pacific whakapapa is only 15 years of age. It compares

32
00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:11.079
with Māori at 26 years of age and Pacifica at 24 years of age, and then non-Māori and non-Pacific,

33
00:04:11.879 --> 00:04:20.920
38 years of age. So the Māori Pacific demographic is half the age of the non-Māori, non-Pacific

34
00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:28.279
population. In demographic terms, this is not simply a young population. It's a very young

35
00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:35.960
population. Many are children now and nearly all are New Zealand's future workforce. We shouldn't

36
00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:43.160
be surprised that they are predominantly based in our major urban areas. Auckland, most prominently,

37
00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:49.640
but also Wellington, Christchurch, and Dunedin, while at the same time establishing growing

38
00:04:49.639 --> 00:04:58.439
footprints in rural and regional areas, such as Northland, Waikato, South Canterbury, Otago, and

39
00:04:58.439 --> 00:05:07.399
in Bikago. This combination matters. It positions this cohort at the intersection of both our urban

40
00:05:07.399 --> 00:05:14.680
productivity engines and our regional revitalisation efforts. So what does this mean for New Zealand's

41
00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:21.400
future productivity and contribution to the workforce? Firstly, quite simply, they will be

42
00:05:21.400 --> 00:05:28.439
essential. As our broader population ages, labour force growth will increasingly depend on Māori

43
00:05:28.439 --> 00:05:34.680
and Pacific peoples and particularly on those with dual whakapapa who are coming of age in

44
00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:41.160
significant numbers. This group will shoulder a growing share of workforce participation,

45
00:05:41.160 --> 00:05:48.200
the tax base, the care economy, and the creative industries. The question is not whether they will

46
00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:54.200
contribute, but whether our systems will be ready to support them to contribute at their full potential.

47
00:05:55.160 --> 00:06:01.240
Secondly, this cohort brings unique strengths that are highly aligned with the future of work.

48
00:06:01.800 --> 00:06:08.040
Many are inherently biocultural or multicultural navigators. They are custom to operating

49
00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:14.840
across worlds, to our Māori and Pacific worlds, home and institution, whenua and city.

50
00:06:16.200 --> 00:06:23.320
In the labour market, increasingly shaped by collaboration, relational skills, adaptability,

51
00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:30.360
and cross-cultural competence, these capabilities are not nice to have. They are productivity

52
00:06:30.360 --> 00:06:37.240
assets. But, and this is where the briefing is deliberately honest, there are also future

53
00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:43.079
challenges if we get this wrong. We are already seeing persistent disparities in educational

54
00:06:43.079 --> 00:06:49.639
attainment, housing security, health outcomes, and exposure to the justice system for Māori

55
00:06:49.639 --> 00:06:55.879
and Pacific peoples. If policy settings fail to recognise the compound realities of young people

56
00:06:55.879 --> 00:07:03.879
with dual identity, we risk reproducing those inequities into the next generation at considerable

57
00:07:03.879 --> 00:07:11.800
social and fiscal cost. There is also a classification challenge. When people are required

58
00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:18.519
to choose a single ethnicity, the lived experience of people can be flattened, and the policy

59
00:07:18.519 --> 00:07:25.079
responses can miss the mark. Education pathways, employment services, and wellbeing supports

60
00:07:25.079 --> 00:07:31.800
are often designed for one identity or another, when the reality for many of these young people

61
00:07:31.800 --> 00:07:40.520
is often both and sometimes neither comfortably. Yet, the opportunities are just as real as the

62
00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:47.000
risks. We can already see amazing glimpses of what this kind of partnership can look like in practice.

63
00:07:47.639 --> 00:07:53.080
The relationship between the Central Pacific Collective and Ngāti Taurangatira provides

64
00:07:53.080 --> 00:08:00.040
a tangible example through the partnership initiatives such as our whāne, where mana whenua

65
00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:06.600
have made available their land for a home ownership approach focused on the delivery of warm,

66
00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:12.600
healthy, long-term homes, homes designed for Pacific people to put down their roots,

67
00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:19.320
rather than cycle through insecurity. These are not homes built in isolation.

68
00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:25.960
They are deliberately located in schools, public transport, health services, and community supports,

69
00:08:25.960 --> 00:08:33.240
recognising that stable housing, access to education, and proximity to care are deeply interconnected.

70
00:08:33.960 --> 00:08:40.440
Ngāti Taurangatira's role as mana whenua brings a strong place-based lens and intergenerational

71
00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:47.160
stewardship, while the Central Pacific Collective contributes deep Pacific-led insight into

72
00:08:47.160 --> 00:08:54.519
whānau needs, affordability pressures, and cultural patterns of living. The project also takes an

73
00:08:54.600 --> 00:09:00.519
inclusive social value approach to delivery, strengthening access to employment and business

74
00:09:00.519 --> 00:09:06.600
opportunities, and helping ensure the economic benefits of development are shared with the

75
00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:13.159
community's most affected by housing need. This approach supports capabilities, skills,

76
00:09:13.159 --> 00:09:19.159
and long-term resilience by remaining open, transparent, and focused on achieving the

77
00:09:19.159 --> 00:09:26.759
best outcomes for whānau communities and the wider system. Together, this approach demonstrates

78
00:09:26.759 --> 00:09:32.519
what is possible when iwi leadership and resources and Pacific community capability are aligned,

79
00:09:32.519 --> 00:09:37.719
creating housing that supports well-being, educational continuity, and workforce

80
00:09:37.719 --> 00:09:44.439
participation over the long term, rather than short-term fixes. For many young people,

81
00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:51.240
with dual Māori and Pacific whakapapa, iwi is really part of their lived reality through

82
00:09:51.240 --> 00:09:58.440
whenua, marae, education, faith, and whānau collections. Creating space for iwi to engage

83
00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:04.520
more closely in conversations about education pathways, employment, well-being, and place-based

84
00:10:04.520 --> 00:10:10.040
development offers an opportunity to ground national policy and local knowledge,

85
00:10:10.759 --> 00:10:14.039
cultural continuity, and intergenerational wisdom.

86
00:10:15.399 --> 00:10:20.839
Just as importantly, this cohort offers New Zealand a chance to foster greater understanding

87
00:10:20.839 --> 00:10:27.159
